# Function to add infos about the type and null values to .describe function
def df_description(df):
    # General description
    description = df.describe(include='all', datetime_is_numeric=True)

    # Types and content of the columns
    description_type = pd.DataFrame(df.dtypes, columns=['type']).T
    number_null = (df.shape[0] - description.loc['count'].T)
    percent_null = (df.shape[0] - description.loc['count'].T)*100/df.shape[0]
    description_null = pd.DataFrame([number_null, percent_null],
                                    index=['number null', 'percentage null'])

    # Concatenate general, type and null stats
    description = pd.concat([description_type, description_null, description])
    return description

1. Merging all datasets into one

We will proceed to merging according to this data structure schema:

- Merging order_items with sellers dataset on seller_id
- Merging order_items with products dataset on product_id
- Merging orders with order_customers dataset on customer_id
- Merging orders with order_items dataset on order_id
- Merging orders with order_payments dataset on order_id
- Merging orders with order_reviews dataset on order_id

# Function that check for outliers on multiple columns
# and count the number of times an outlier appeared.
# If an outlier appeared at least n times,
# we drop that outlier from the dataset.
def Outliers_Limits(df, col_list, n, IQR_multiplier):
    indexes_outliers = []
    # Checking for outliers and getting their index
    for col in col_list:
        Q1 = df[col].quantile(0.25)
        Q3 = df[col].quantile(0.75)
        IQR = Q3 - Q1
        lower_limit = (Q1 - IQR_multiplier*IQR)
        upper_limit = (Q3 + IQR_multiplier*IQR)
        list_outliers = df[(df[col] < lower_limit)
                           | (df[col] > upper_limit)].index
        indexes_outliers.extend(list_outliers)

    # Counting the number of time an outlier appeared
    indexes_outliers = Counter(indexes_outliers)

    # Selection of outliers appearing at least n time
    multiple_outliers = list(k for k, v in indexes_outliers.items() if v > n)
    print('Number of outliers to remove: {}'.format(len(multiple_outliers)))

    # Dropping those outliers that appeared at least n time
    df.drop(multiple_outliers, axis=0, inplace=True)

3. Feature Engineering

Features that will be created:

  • nbr_orders: Number of times the customers purchased
  • time_since_last_order_h: the time since last order made by the customer
  • payment_value: Mean amount of purchase(s) per customer
  • review_score: Mean review score per customer
  • delivery_time_h: Mean difference between order_purchase_timestamp
    and order_delivered_customer_date per customer
  • nbr_late_delivery: Number of late delivery per customer

We will do two sets of test: the happy and unhappy customers.

  • The first test will use the RFM segmentation and includes 3 features:
    nbr_orders, time_since_last_order_h, and payment_value.
  • The second test will use the RFM and review score features to detect\
  • The third test will use the RFM, review score, and delivery time features to detect
    the problem of delivery and it's effect on the review score and the customer caracteristics.

# Converting all date columns to datetime type
date_columns = ['order_purchase_timestamp',
                'order_approved_at',
                'order_delivered_carrier_date',
                'order_delivered_customer_date',
                'order_estimated_delivery_date']

# Cretaing three columns delivery_time, estimated_vs_actual_delivery_date,
# and late_delivery that will be used later for the feature engineering
orders_data['delivery_time(h)'] = (orders_data['order_delivered_customer_date']
                                   - orders_data['order_purchase_timestamp'])\
                                  .astype('timedelta64[h]')

# Function that plot the distributions of some numerical columns
# for each categorcical columns
def distribution_of_num_for_each_categ(df, columns_list, cat_columns, n_col):
    n_sub = len(columns_list)
    for cat_column in cat_columns:
        fig, axes = plt.subplots(int(round((0.49+n_sub/n_col), 0)), n_col,
                                 figsize=(20, int(3.6*n_sub/n_col)))
        axes = np.array(axes)
        i = 0
        cat_list = df.groupby(by=cat_column).nunique()\
                     .sort_values(cat_column, ascending=True).head(10).index
        for ax in axes.reshape(-1):
            groupes = []
            for m in cat_list:
                groupes.append(df[df[cat_column] == m][columns_list[i]])
            ax.boxplot(groupes, labels=cat_list, showfliers=False,
                       vert=False, patch_artist=True, showmeans=True)
            ax.set_xlabel(format(columns_list[i]))
            if i % n_col == 0:
                ax.set_ylabel(format(cat_column))
            i += 1
        plt.show()

C. Multivariate analysis

We will start standardizing the data, then we perform dimension reduction using t-SNE.
The use of t-SNE is due to the non-linear relation between the features as seen in the analysis section.
t-SNE will be performed on three sets of features:

  • the RFM features
  • the RFM features with the review score
  • the RFM features with the review score and the delivery time

fig, axes = plt.subplots(1, 5, figsize=(20, 4))
colomns_list = ['time_since_last_order_h', 'nbr_orders',
                'payment_value', 'review_score',
                'delivery_time_h']
i = 0
for col in colomns_list:
    data = cust_uniq_df_tsne[cust_uniq_df_tsne[col]
                             <= cust_uniq_df_tsne[col].median()*5]
    sns.scatterplot(data=data,
                    x='Dim_1_RFM_RS_DT_tsne',
                    y='Dim_2_RFM_RS_DT_tsne',
                    hue=col,
                    ax=axes[i])
    axes[i].set_xlim(-200, 200)
    axes[i].set_ylim(-200, 200)
    plt.setp(axes[i].get_legend().get_texts(), fontsize='8')  # for legend text
    plt.setp(axes[i].get_legend().get_title(), fontsize='8')  # for legend titl
    i += 1
plt.show()

Observations:

  • For time since last order feature, customers that made purchase recently have lower dimension 1
    and higher dimension 2 values in t-SNE than the customers that made purchase long time ago.
  • For nbr of orders feature, customers that made multiple orders have high
    dimension 2 value in t-SNE than customers that made only one order.
  • For payment value feature, it's hard to assign regions.
  • For review score feature, customers that gave good review score have lower
    dimension 1 value in t-SNE than the customers that gave low review score.
  • For delivery time, customers that had long delivery time had higher
    dimension 1 value in t-SNE.
